===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}

{{liushu|p}} – {{och-l|又|hand}} holding a stylized flag almost identical to {{och-l|中}} perhaps to indicate a representative or ambassador (see its variant [[吏]] used in [[使]] to mean "ambassador"). As an alternative, it holds either a pen or a hunting weapon resembling similar to 中. Hence, the inner component 中 is partly unclear.

The whole character originally indicates the act of taking notes; today, it means "history". Compare [[事]].

===Etymology===
;"to send, to employ, to cause"
:Causative derivation of {{och-l|理|tr=rəʔ}} "envoy ({{w|Zuozhuan|Zuo}})" , "jail-official" ({{w|Guanzi}}), "[[matchmaker|marriage go-between]]", which is perhaps the same word as {{och-l|理|tr=rəʔ}} "to administer" {{zh-ref|(Schuessler 2007)}}; the sense "scribe, historian" is derived from this.

;"scribe, historian"
:Possibly from {{der|zh|aav}}; {{zh-ref|Schuessler (2007)}} compared {{och-l|理}}, {{och-l|吏|official}}, {{och-l|史|scribe, historian}}, and {{och-l|使|ambassador}} to {{cog|okz|re||to move, change position}} & its derivatives {{cog|okz|pre||to send, order, assign, appoint, delegate, use, employ, make}}, in turn related to {{m|okz|paṃre||to serve; service, duty; servant, delegate, representative, minister}}; with Sino-Tibetan causative *''s-'' corresponding to Khmer causative *''p-''.
:Alternatively, {{zh-ref|Unger (1990)}} and {{zh-ref|Starostin & Peiros (1996)}} derived {{och-l|史}} "scribe, secretary" from {{och-l|理}} "to mark, to draw lines", which, while cognate with {{cog|bo|འབྲི||to write, to draw}}, apparently never meant "to write, to record".

